## Rule #5 — Scope of Responsibility

Each module has well-defined boundaries. See `.claude/rules/scope-responsibilities.md` for the full map.

| Role | Responsibility | CANNOT contain |
|------|----------------|----------------|
{{#each modules}}
{{#if (eq role "frontend")}}
| {{name}} (frontend) | Layout, UX, visual states, API calls | Domain calculations, business rules |
{{else if (eq role "backend")}}
| {{name}} (backend) | Validations, calculations, domain rules, APIs | UI logic, DDL, AI pipelines |
{{else if (eq role "database")}}
| {{name}} (database) | DDL, migrations, indexes, constraints | Business logic, application code |
{{else if (eq role "agent-ai")}}
| {{name}} (agent-ai) | Rules, pipelines, LLM, schedulers | API/frontend logic |
{{else if (eq role "e2e")}}
| {{name}} (e2e) | BDD features, step definitions, page objects | Application code |
{{else if (eq role "mobile")}}
| {{name}} (mobile) | Layout, UX, native navigation, API calls | Domain calculations, business rules |
{{else}}
| {{name}} ({{role}}) | As defined in module CLAUDE.md | As defined in module CLAUDE.md |
{{/if}}
{{/each}}

**Golden Rule**: Frontends are pure visual layer. All business logic belongs to the backend/BFF.

**Auto-routing**: during planning, business logic → BFF mandatory. Engine/pipeline logic → Agent. Full rule: `.claude/rules/scope-responsibilities.md`
{{/ifRule}}

## Development Methodology

{{#ifRule "feature-planning-gate"}}
**5-Phase Planning** — Outside-In with mandatory gates:

| Phase | Name | What it does | Gate |
|-------|------|-------------|------|
| 1 | **Discovery** | Agent asks 10-20 business questions, searches existing patterns | User confirms all answered |
| 2 | **Business Refinement** | Documents rules in Given-When-Then per module. Marks `[NEEDS CLARIFICATION]` | User approves rules |
| 3 | **Technical Design** | Contract-First: API + schema BEFORE code. Mandatory reuse check | User approves contracts |
| 4 | **Tasks** | Order: schema → API contracts → frontend → backend → integration | User approves tasks |
| 5 | **Implementation** | TDD per task (Red → Green), contract vs actual reconciliation | — |

- **Outside-In**: UI (components) → contracts → backend routes → data sources
- **Execution**: {{#if hasDatabase}}database → {{/if}}backend{{#if hasAgent}} → agent{{/if}}{{#if hasFrontend}} → frontend{{/if}}
- **Contract-First**: NEVER implement an endpoint without an approved contract. NEVER create a component without checking for reuse.
- **Enforcement hooks**: `pre-edit.sh`, `planning-eval.sh`, `planning-validator.sh`

{{/ifRule}}
**ALWAYS plan before executing:**
1. **Analyze** — Use Explore agents to understand scope and existing patterns
2. **Think** — Extended thinking for tradeoffs
3. **Plan** — Approach with justification{{#ifRule "feature-planning-gate"}}. New features → `/plan-feature` (5 phases with gates){{/ifRule}}
{{#ifRule "tdd-enforcement"}}
4. **Test (Red)** — Delegate test writing BEFORE implementation
5. **Execute (Green)** — Delegate minimum implementation to pass tests
6. **Validate** — Only affected modules
{{else}}
4. **Execute** — Delegate implementation to the correct agent
5. **Validate** — Only affected modules
{{/ifRule}}

{{#ifRule "tdd-enforcement"}}
**Mandatory TDD** — For every testable task:
- **Features**: Delegate writes tests{{#ifRule "feature-planning-gate"}} based on the test plan (Given-When-Then){{/ifRule}} → fail (Red) → implement → pass (Green)
- **Bug fixes**: Test that reproduces the bug → fail (Red) → fix → pass (Green)
- **Refactoring**: Ensure existing tests pass → refactor → tests still pass

**Skill**: `/tdd` orchestrates the full cycle automatically with context isolation.
{{/ifRule}}

{{#ifRule "feature-planning-gate"}}
## Feature Planning Gate (Rule #3)

> **ABSOLUTE BLOCK.** No feature can be implemented without docs on disk.

**Mandatory auto-detection** — the orchestrator MUST detect "new feature" and invoke `/plan-feature` automatically.

**Pre-implementation checklist:**
1. Is it a new feature? (keywords: implement, create, add, new module)
2. If YES → do `{{paths.docsRoot}}/{{paths.rules}}/{module}/{{paths.businessRules}}/{feature}.md` exist in affected modules?
3. If NO → Classify Simple/Complex → `/plan-feature` (5 phases with gates)
4. If YES → Use `{{paths.devPlans}}/{feature}.md` as implementation guide

**Classification**: SIMPLE when ALL: max 2 modules, standard CRUD, no new concept, clear pattern, no new integration, no complex rules. Any failure → COMPLEX.

**NOT a feature**: bug fix, refactoring, config/adjustment, layout fix.

**Docs per module**: For each affected module, 3 files in `{{paths.docsRoot}}/{{paths.rules}}/{module}/`:
- `{{paths.businessRules}}/{feature}.md` — business rules (Given-When-Then)
- `{{paths.testPlans}}/{feature}.md` — test plan (Gherkin)
- `{{paths.devPlans}}/{feature}.md` — atomic tasks with rule traceability

**Reuse Check**: Before creating ANY new endpoint or component, search for existing ones with Grep. Document the reuse decision.

**Skill**: `/plan-feature` orchestrates 5 phases with mandatory gates.
{{/ifRule}}

{{#ifRule "changelog-by-date"}}
## Commit with Changelog (Rule #1)

Every completed delegation generates a **structured git commit** per submodule. History lives in `git log`, not in files.

### Commit Format

```
feat({module}): short change title

Agent: {sub-agent}
Status: Completed | Failed
Decision: {approach justification}

Changes:
- path/file (Created|Modified|Removed): description
{{#ifRule "conditional-mermaid"}}
Diagram: (if architectural change — mermaid in commit body)
{{/ifRule}}
```

### Rules
- One commit per completed delegation, in the affected submodule
- Use Conventional Commits: `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `chore`
- **Orchestrator's responsibility** (not sub-agent's): `git add {submodule} && git commit`
- To check history: `git log --oneline {submodule}/`
{{/ifRule}}

{{#ifRule "conditional-mermaid"}}
## Mermaid Diagrams (Rule #2)

| Scenario | Diagram Type |
|----------|-------------|
| New endpoint | sequenceDiagram |
| DB schema | erDiagram |
| New component | flowchart LR |
| AI pipeline | flowchart TD |

**Exceptions** (do NOT generate diagram): simple bug fix, config, refactoring, basic CRUD.

Syntax reference and templates: `.claude/{{docsRoot}}/templates/mermaid-reference.md`
{{/ifRule}}

{{#ifRule "api-response-contract"}}
## API Response Contract (Rule #4)

```
Success (list): {"data": [...], "meta": {"total": N, "page": 1}}
Success (item): {"data": {...}}
Error:          {"error": {"message": "...", "code": "VALIDATION_ERROR"}}
```

All endpoints MUST follow this envelope. No exceptions.
{{/ifRule}}

{{#ifRule "tdd-sequential-enforcement"}}
## Rule #9 — TDD Sequential Enforcement

**ABSOLUTE BLOCK.** No delegate can write tests AND implementation in the same invocation.

**Problem**: When a delegate (e.g., front-delegate, bff-delegate) creates tests and code together, TDD hooks (`pre-edit.sh`) don't detect the violation — timestamps are identical, TDD compliance drops to ~20%.

**Rule**: Every testable task MUST use **two separate invocations**:

| Phase | Agent | Sees | Produces | Validation |
|-------|-------|------|----------|------------|
| **Red** | `tdd-test-writer` | Business specs/rules, existing `tests/` | Tests that FAIL | Run tests → confirm FAILURE |
| **Green** | `tdd-implementer` | Failing tests + existing `src/` | Minimum implementation | Run tests → confirm PASS |

**Prohibitions**:
- Direct delegate (front-delegate, bff-delegate, etc.) **CANNOT** create files in `tests/` AND `src/` in the same invocation
- If orchestrator delegates implementation to a direct delegate, the delegate receives ONLY implementation task — tests must already exist
- **NEVER** skip failure validation between Red and Green

**Exceptions** (direct delegate allowed for tests + code together):
- Bug fix with regression test (scope < 3 files)
- Refactoring where tests already exist and must continue passing
- Config/adjustment without business logic

**Skill**: `/tdd` orchestrates the full cycle automatically with context isolation.

Full rule: `.claude/rules/tdd/sequential-enforcement.md`
{{/ifRule}}

{{#ifRule "e2e-test-protection"}}
## E2E Protection (Rule #6)

E2E tests are protected by TWO layers: deny rules (Claude Code) + chmod 555/444 (OS).

**Protected files**: `features/**/*.feature` + `step-definitions/**/*.ts`
**Free files**: `support/**` (page objects, fixtures, mock server)

| Directory | Status | Reason |
|-----------|--------|--------|
| `features/` | Protected | BDD scenarios are specification |
| `step-definitions/` | Protected | Steps are contract |
| `support/` | Free | Page objects, fixtures, helpers |

**100% manual user toggle**:
- `make e2e-unlock` — allows chmod writing (Red phase)
- `make e2e-lock` — locks chmod on test directories/files
- Deny rules in `.claude/settings.json` block Edit/Write permanently
- The orchestrator NEVER executes `e2e-unlock` or removes deny rules
- Safety net: `make test-e2e` and `make dev` run `e2e-lock` automatically

**Workflow**:
- **Red phase**: User runs `make e2e-unlock` → write tests → `make e2e-lock`
- **Green phase**: Tests locked. Implement until tests pass.
- **Refactor**: Repeat Red phase if tests need changes.

**NEVER** modify tests to make them pass. The code under test must change.
{{/ifRule}}

{{#ifRule "post-dev-e2e-validation"}}
## Post-Dev E2E Validation (Rule #7)

**Trigger**: after implementation affecting frontend, mobile, or BFF.

**Absolute guardrail**: E2E directories are UNTOUCHABLE during the diagnostic loop. No file — features, step definitions, support — can be altered. The fix is ALWAYS in application code.

**If all tests pass** → continue normal flow.

**If any test fails** → Diagnostic Loop (max 3 attempts):
1. Analyze test output — identify failing scenarios and error messages
2. Investigate root cause in APPLICATION code (NEVER in E2E)
3. Delegate fix to the correct delegate — NEVER to e2e-delegate
4. Re-run E2E tests
5. If passed → continue. If failed → back to step 1

**After 3 iterations without success**: STOP and report to user with diagnostics:
- Failing scenarios and error messages
- Root cause hypothesis
- Correction attempts made
- User decides if tests need updating (via `make e2e-unlock`)

**Scope**: Includes BFF changes (not just frontend), as endpoint/contract changes can break E2E behavior.

> Reinforces Rule #6: NEVER modify E2E tests to make code pass.
{{/ifRule}}

{{#ifRule "execution-trace"}}
## Rule #10 — Execution Observability

Three mechanisms ensure traceability:

1. **Plan Checkpoint** (pre-execution) — Present decomposition to user and await approval before delegating
2. **Spec-Validate** (post-implementation) — Invoke `/spec-validate` after each Green phase to verify 100% conformance
3. **Trace File** (during execution) — Append-only at `{{paths.docsRoot}}/trace/{feature}-{YYYY-MM-DD}.md` recording every delegation

**Enforcement**: No checkpoint approval → delegation blocked. If conformance < 100% → re-delegate (max 2 iterations) → escalate to user.

**Exemptions**: Bug fix (< 3 files), refactoring, config — trace created but approval optional.
{{/ifRule}}

{{#ifRule "parallel-delegation"}}
## Rule #11 — Parallel Delegation

Independent delegates **MUST** run in parallel via multiple `Agent` tool calls **in the same message**.

**Dependency graph**: `database` → `backend`/`agent-ai` → `frontend`/`mobile`

**Algorithm**: Group into waves — each wave contains modules with no mutual dependencies. Launch each wave in parallel, await completion before the next.

{{#ifRule "tdd-sequential-enforcement"}}
**TDD in parallel**: Parallel Red and Green across different modules. Red→Green of the SAME module remains sequential (Rule #9).
{{/ifRule}}

**Partial failure**: If one delegate fails, others in the same wave continue. Dependent waves are blocked.
{{/ifRule}}

{{#if (or (lookup methodology.rules "tdd-enforcement") (lookup methodology.rules "feature-planning-gate"))}}
## Enforcement Hooks

The following automatic hooks are active in this project:

| Hook | Event | Function |
|------|-------|----------|
| `pre-edit.sh` | PreToolUse (Edit/Write) | Consolidated guard: TDD + Planning Gate |
{{#ifRule "tdd-enforcement"}}
| `auto-test.sh` | PostToolUse (Edit/Write) | Runs related test automatically |
| `tdd-eval.sh` | UserPromptSubmit | Evaluates TDD cycle in user prompt |
{{/ifRule}}
{{#ifRule "feature-planning-gate"}}
| `planning-validator.sh` | PostToolUse (Edit/Write) | Validates consistency with approved plan |
| `planning-eval.sh` | UserPromptSubmit | Evaluates planning needs in prompt |
{{/ifRule}}
| `post-dev-verify.sh` | Stop | Final verification before ending |

{{#ifRule "tdd-enforcement"}}
**Context Isolation** — For features, use dedicated TDD sub-agents:
- `tdd-test-writer`: Sees ONLY business specs → writes tests (Red)
- `tdd-implementer`: Sees ONLY failing tests → implements (Green)

**Skill `/tdd`** — Orchestrates full TDD cycle: Feature Gate → Test Writer (Red) → Implementer (Green) → Validation.

**Why**: Without enforcement, TDD compliance with AI agents is ~20%. With hooks + context isolation, it rises to ~84%.
{{/ifRule}}

